name: Eric Balchunas
tweet: @EtfHearsay @TheTerminal The problem with semi-transparent ETFs isn't their transparency IMO, it is that they are neither super cheap or super active. As portfolio barbel the flows do to and most semi's are benchmark sensitive and 40-60bp fee. That 'middle ground' is tough spot to be moving fwd.

name: Eric Balchunas
tweet: @TheTerminal @tpsarofagis $LCTU assets are one institution who pre-seeded the fund (still counts and is interesting but very dif than grassroots demand). This is the case with a few ESG ETFs. Further, BlackRock put them in its own models. All told only approx 60% of the assets are grassroots flows.

name: Eric Balchunas
tweet: @TheTerminal Final thought, bc BlackRock and Vgrd have been pretty committed to advancing ESG via their voting, thus buy simply holding a cheap index fund you are kinda being ESG in a way given they have decent influence with their 8% ownership.

name: Eric Balchunas
tweet: @TheTerminal Further we think the ESG label will be slapped on so much and create confusion. Some of the stocks in ESG ETFs will surprise people and some of the stocks excluded will surprise them. It's so subjective. All this is headwind IMO.

name: Eric Balchunas
tweet: @TheTerminal Asset growth yes, but $1T is overly-optimistic IMO. Many ESG ETFs are looking to replace the core of a portfolio and to dislodge a 3bp SPX ETF like $VOO is harder than it looks. That said I am bullish on clean energy ETFs like $TAN $ICLN bc they can be added on to a $VOO.
